{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/physical-computing/project-1/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"fridge notes"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"d9b99c56-49d8-5c57-95e5-0bc55df108c0","excerpt":"Project 1 A big issue I ran into this project was waiting for parts to arrive. I ran with the suggestion to acquire neopixels to make a grid. I ended up buying…","html":"<h2>Project 1</h2>\n<p>A big issue I ran into this project was waiting for parts to arrive. I ran with the suggestion to acquire neopixels to make a grid. I ended up buying the wrong ones (a strip instead of a matrix), so I had to cut and re-solder to make a flexible grid.</p>\n<h1>Hardware</h1>\n<p>This was my first attempt at a solder (ever!). I think I did ok, and I definitely got better as I went along.\n<span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/98e93a98a62d9c4adf9509d8b0c62a38/0f98f/soldering1.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 56.08108108108109%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"first solder\"\n        title=\"first solder\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/98e93a98a62d9c4adf9509d8b0c62a38/1c72d/soldering1.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/98e93a98a62d9c4adf9509d8b0c62a38/a80bd/soldering1.jpg 148w,\n/blog/static/98e93a98a62d9c4adf9509d8b0c62a38/1c91a/soldering1.jpg 295w,\n/blog/static/98e93a98a62d9c4adf9509d8b0c62a38/1c72d/soldering1.jpg 590w,\n/blog/static/98e93a98a62d9c4adf9509d8b0c62a38/a8a14/soldering1.jpg 885w,\n/blog/static/98e93a98a62d9c4adf9509d8b0c62a38/fbd2c/soldering1.jpg 1180w,\n/blog/static/98e93a98a62d9c4adf9509d8b0c62a38/0f98f/soldering1.jpg 1920w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Final soldering result. It is now in the grid shape that I want to use for my etch-a-sketch.\n<span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/0c1231c1e68674ff35a384127f855042/29114/soldering6.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 56.08108108108109%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"final solder\"\n        title=\"final solder\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/0c1231c1e68674ff35a384127f855042/fcda8/soldering6.png\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/0c1231c1e68674ff35a384127f855042/12f09/soldering6.png 148w,\n/blog/static/0c1231c1e68674ff35a384127f855042/e4a3f/soldering6.png 295w,\n/blog/static/0c1231c1e68674ff35a384127f855042/fcda8/soldering6.png 590w,\n/blog/static/0c1231c1e68674ff35a384127f855042/efc66/soldering6.png 885w,\n/blog/static/0c1231c1e68674ff35a384127f855042/c83ae/soldering6.png 1180w,\n/blog/static/0c1231c1e68674ff35a384127f855042/29114/soldering6.png 1920w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>While going back and forth between my stovetop (where I had a vent and can solder in my apartment), my cat took over my work station.\n<span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/bbfd7ee214863f214392ff7b18f81297/0f98f/cat-break.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 56.08108108108109%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"cat break\"\n        title=\"cat break\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/bbfd7ee214863f214392ff7b18f81297/1c72d/cat-break.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/bbfd7ee214863f214392ff7b18f81297/a80bd/cat-break.jpg 148w,\n/blog/static/bbfd7ee214863f214392ff7b18f81297/1c91a/cat-break.jpg 295w,\n/blog/static/bbfd7ee214863f214392ff7b18f81297/1c72d/cat-break.jpg 590w,\n/blog/static/bbfd7ee214863f214392ff7b18f81297/a8a14/cat-break.jpg 885w,\n/blog/static/bbfd7ee214863f214392ff7b18f81297/fbd2c/cat-break.jpg 1180w,\n/blog/static/bbfd7ee214863f214392ff7b18f81297/0f98f/cat-break.jpg 1920w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<h1>Software</h1>\n<p>Next was thinking about the code I wanted to create. I wanted to use two potentiometers as the two etch-a-sketch wheels that move the lines around. </p>\n<p>Using the <code class=\"language-text\">Adafruit_NeoPixel</code> library, you can light up the leds using the neopixel object, like so:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">// constructor with parameters of number of pixels (30), pin number (10)\nAdafruit_NeoPixel strip = Adafruit_NeoPixel(NUMPIXELS, 10);\n\n// setting the individual led number (1) to specified color\nstrip.setPixelColor(1, strip.Color(0, 75, 75));\n\n// displaying the color\nstrip.show(); </code></pre></div>\n<p>I needed to find a way to store the information of where the light should be lit. The led strip itself keeps track of the leds in order, numbered 0-29. I needed to find a way to create a 2D array to easily keep track of rows and columns, so I created a constant array:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">const int leds[5][6] = \n    {{0,1,2,3,4,5},\n    {11,10,9,8,7,6}, \n    {12,13,14,15,16,17}, \n    {23,22,21,20,19,18},\n    {24,25,26,27,28,29}};</code></pre></div>\n<p>Notice how these aren’t in numerical order. This is because the “grid” of leds flows in one direction.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/46baa7903a61f18746791b8fce16ed57/0f98f/soldering7.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 56.08108108108109%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"flow of power\"\n        title=\"flow of power\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/46baa7903a61f18746791b8fce16ed57/1c72d/soldering7.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/46baa7903a61f18746791b8fce16ed57/a80bd/soldering7.jpg 148w,\n/blog/static/46baa7903a61f18746791b8fce16ed57/1c91a/soldering7.jpg 295w,\n/blog/static/46baa7903a61f18746791b8fce16ed57/1c72d/soldering7.jpg 590w,\n/blog/static/46baa7903a61f18746791b8fce16ed57/a8a14/soldering7.jpg 885w,\n/blog/static/46baa7903a61f18746791b8fce16ed57/fbd2c/soldering7.jpg 1180w,\n/blog/static/46baa7903a61f18746791b8fce16ed57/0f98f/soldering7.jpg 1920w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>So, the numbers needed to reflect the grid itself and the order the led is on the strip. Which is how we got two rows that are in reverse order, we have two led strips that are in the opposite direction.</p>\n<p>From there, I needed to figure out the best way to move the lights. Since it relied on potentiometers, it could dial between the “rows” and “columns”.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">// handling rows\nif(rightSwitch &lt; 1023 / 2 &amp;&amp; row &gt; 0){\n    row -= 1;\n}\nif(rightSwitch &gt;= 1023 / 2 &amp;&amp; row &lt; 4){\n    row +=1;\n}\n\nif(leftSwitch &lt; 1023 / 2 &amp;&amp; column &gt; 0){\n    column -= 1;\n}\nif(leftSwitch &gt;= 1023 / 2 &amp;&amp; column &lt; 5){\n    column +=1;\n}\n\ndelay(1000);</code></pre></div>\n<p>Pretty simple logic. It will add and subtract based on the halfway point. This does mean drawing in the middle is challenging, but so is an etch-a-sketch. I also added a delay so the numbers wouldn’t change too quickly.</p>\n<p>I added a carboard housing to cover up the wires of the led strips, but the arduino wouldn’t fit underneath without being crushed. So I left it outside the housing.</p>\n<p>Once I got to testing this, I realized I would lose where the led was “resting”, like so:</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/aaea3bf1036d1e7dd2e8362e14126ee8/0f98f/testing.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 56.08108108108109%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"testing\"\n        title=\"testing\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/aaea3bf1036d1e7dd2e8362e14126ee8/1c72d/testing.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/aaea3bf1036d1e7dd2e8362e14126ee8/a80bd/testing.jpg 148w,\n/blog/static/aaea3bf1036d1e7dd2e8362e14126ee8/1c91a/testing.jpg 295w,\n/blog/static/aaea3bf1036d1e7dd2e8362e14126ee8/1c72d/testing.jpg 590w,\n/blog/static/aaea3bf1036d1e7dd2e8362e14126ee8/a8a14/testing.jpg 885w,\n/blog/static/aaea3bf1036d1e7dd2e8362e14126ee8/fbd2c/testing.jpg 1180w,\n/blog/static/aaea3bf1036d1e7dd2e8362e14126ee8/0f98f/testing.jpg 1920w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>I didn’t know where the drawing left off. So I wrote some code using a previous class exercise:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">// find where led is &#39;resting&#39;\ncurrent = leds[row][column];\nledTracking[row][column]=1;\n\nstrip.setPixelColor(current, strip.Color(0, 75, 75));\nif(current == previous){\n    strip.setPixelColor(current, strip.Color(75, 0, 0));\n} else{\n    strip.setPixelColor(previous, strip.Color(0, 75, 75));\n}\nprevious = current;\nstrip.show(); </code></pre></div>\n<p>Effectively this makes the led red when it is “resting”, or when the previous and current state are the same.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/2ae2daf2261e7eabaa10b0112b4dddfe/0f98f/final.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 56.08108108108109%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"final\"\n        title=\"final\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/2ae2daf2261e7eabaa10b0112b4dddfe/1c72d/final.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/2ae2daf2261e7eabaa10b0112b4dddfe/a80bd/final.jpg 148w,\n/blog/static/2ae2daf2261e7eabaa10b0112b4dddfe/1c91a/final.jpg 295w,\n/blog/static/2ae2daf2261e7eabaa10b0112b4dddfe/1c72d/final.jpg 590w,\n/blog/static/2ae2daf2261e7eabaa10b0112b4dddfe/a8a14/final.jpg 885w,\n/blog/static/2ae2daf2261e7eabaa10b0112b4dddfe/fbd2c/final.jpg 1180w,\n/blog/static/2ae2daf2261e7eabaa10b0112b4dddfe/0f98f/final.jpg 1920w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Now I know where the led will start drawing from! </p>\n<p>I also added the speaker to play a tune once you made the final shape!!</p>\n<p><div class=\"gatsby-resp-iframe-wrapper\" style=\"padding-bottom: 50%; position: relative; height: 0; overflow: hidden; \" > <div class=\"embedVideo-container\"> <iframe title src=\"https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/35pBfFxisrs?rel=0\" class=\"embedVideo-iframe\" style=\"border:0; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; \" allowfullscreen></iframe> </div> </div></p>\n<p>And here is my final code:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">#include &lt;Adafruit_NeoPixel.h&gt;\n#include &quot;pitches.h&quot;\n\n#define NUMPIXELS 30 \n\nAdafruit_NeoPixel strip = Adafruit_NeoPixel(NUMPIXELS, 10);\n\nconst int leds[5][6] = {\n    {0,1,2,3,4,5},\n    {11,10,9,8,7,6}, \n    {12,13,14,15,16,17}, \n    {23,22,21,20,19,18},\n    {24,25,26,27,28,29}};\nint ledTracking[5][6] = {};\nconst int speakerPin = 11; \nint notes[] = {\nNOTE_A4, NOTE_B4, NOTE_C3 };  \n\nvoid setup() {\npinMode(A5, INPUT);\nstrip.begin();\nSerial.begin(9600);\n\nstrip.clear();\nstrip.setPixelColor(1, strip.Color(0, 75, 75));\nstrip.show(); \n}\n\nint row = 1;\nint column = 1;\nint light = 1;\nint current = 0;\nint previous = 0;\n\nvoid loop() {\n\nfloat rightSwitch = analogRead(A5);\nfloat leftSwitch = analogRead(A4);\n\n// handling rows\nif(rightSwitch &lt; 1023 / 2 &amp;&amp; row &gt; 0){\n    row -= 1;\n}\nif(rightSwitch &gt;= 1023 / 2 &amp;&amp; row &lt; 4){\n    row +=1;\n}\n\nif(leftSwitch &lt; 1023 / 2 &amp;&amp; column &gt; 0){\n    column -= 1;\n}\nif(leftSwitch &gt;= 1023 / 2 &amp;&amp; column &lt; 5){\n    column +=1;\n}\n\ndelay(1000);\n\n// find where led is &#39;resting&#39;\ncurrent = leds[row][column];\nledTracking[row][column]=1;\n\nstrip.setPixelColor(current, strip.Color(0, 75, 75));\nif(current == previous){\n    strip.setPixelColor(current, strip.Color(75, 0, 0));\n} else{\n    strip.setPixelColor(previous, strip.Color(0, 75, 75));\n}\nprevious = current;\nstrip.show(); \n\n// music based on led shape (square)\nif(ledTracking[0][0] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[0][1] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[0][2] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[0][3] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[0][4] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[0][5] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[1][0] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[2][0] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[3][0] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[4][0] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[1][5] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[2][5] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[3][5] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[4][5] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[4][4] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[4][3] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[4][2] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[4][1] == 1 &amp;&amp;\n    ledTracking[4][0] == 1){ \n    tone(speakerPin, notes[0], 20);\n    tone(speakerPin, notes[1], 20);\n    tone(speakerPin, notes[3], 20);\n}\n}</code></pre></div>","frontmatter":{"title":"Project 1","date":"October 06, 2020","description":null}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/physical-computing/project-1/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/visual-language/assignment-4/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Week 6 Composition"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/visual-language/assignment-5/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Week 7 Logo"}}}},"staticQueryHashes":["2841359383","3257411868"]}